  "prompt": "What is the meaning of f(2) in calculus?",
  "response": "In calculus, the notation \\( f(2) \\) represents the value of the function \\( f \\) when the input (or the argument) is 2. Essentially, it is asking for the output of the function \\( f \\) at the point where the input is 2.\n\nFor example, if \\( f(x) = x^2 \\), then \\( f(2) \\) would be calculated as follows:\n\\[ f(2) = 2^2 = 4 \\]\n\nSo, \\( f(2) \\) in this case equals 4.\n\nThis notation is used to evaluate functions at specific points, which is a common operation in calculus and other areas of mathematics.",
